## 5. Database Design

### Three Databases, Three Purposes

Atrosha uses three completely different databases, each chosen for what it's best at:

#### PostgreSQL via Supabase — Business Data (User & Org State)

This is the "source of truth" for who your customers are. Managed by Supabase, which runs PostgreSQL under the hood with added features:

**Key Tables:**

```sql
-- Organizations (each company using Atrosha)
organizations (
    id UUID PRIMARY KEY,
    name TEXT NOT NULL,
    plan_tier TEXT NOT NULL,           -- 'explorer' | 'growth' | 'enterprise'
    subscription_status TEXT,          -- 'active' | 'canceled' | 'trialing'
    stripe_customer_id TEXT,           -- links to Stripe
    stripe_subscription_id TEXT,
    created_at TIMESTAMPTZ,
    updated_at TIMESTAMPTZ
)

-- Users (people who log in to the dashboard)
-- Managed entirely by Supabase Auth — user records in auth.users
-- user_metadata stores: { org_name, plan_tier }
```

**Why Supabase Auth instead of rolling your own?**
Rolling your own auth (bcrypt, sessions, refresh tokens, email verification, magic links, OAuth) is a multi-week project that introduces security bugs. Supabase Auth is a production-hardened system based on GoTrue (used by millions). The `@supabase/ssr` package handles cookie-based sessions that work correctly with Next.js Server Components and Server Actions.

#### Redis — Ephemeral Operational Data (Hot Path)

Redis is an in-memory key-value store. Everything that needs to be read/written on the hot request path lives here because Redis latency is typically **< 1ms**, vs. PostgreSQL's **5–20ms**.

Key schema:
```
atrosha:{org_id}:keys:{agent_id}    → Ed25519 public key (hex string)
atrosha:{org_id}:role:{agent_id}    → "agent" | "admin"
atrosha:usage:{agent_id}            → current spend (float)
atrosha:limit:{agent_id}            → budget limit (float)
circuit:{agent_id}                  → consecutive denial count (integer)
```

**Eviction:** Redis is configured with no TTL on most keys (they're persistent for the life of the agent registration). Circuit breaker keys expire in 300 seconds automatically.

**What happens if Redis goes down?**
The proxy is designed to degrade gracefully:
- Signature verification falls back to the hardcoded demo agent-007 key
- Circuit breaker `is_open()` returns `false` (fail-open)
- Policy check for agent-007 hardcoded to return OK
- Most real agents would get `KeyNotFound` → 401 Unauthorized

This "fail-open" philosophy means the proxy never becomes a total outage, but security degrades to "at least don't crash" mode.

#### ClickHouse — Append-Only Analytics (Audit Logs)

ClickHouse is used purely for audit logs. It's optimized for write-heavy, query-heavy analytics on immutable time-series data.

The `MergeTree` engine with `PARTITION BY toYYYYMMDD(ts)` means:
- Each day of data is stored in a separate data part on disk
- Queries for "last 7 days" only touch 7 partitions — the rest aren't even read
- `TTL ts + INTERVAL 365 DAY` auto-deletes data older than 1 year

**Ordering key `(org_id, agent_id, ts)`:** When you query "show me all transactions for agent X in org Y sorted by time," ClickHouse reads a contiguous block of disk — maximum efficiency.

