## 13. Why These Technologies?

### Why Rust for the Proxy (not Node.js, Go, or Python)?

| Language | Pros | Cons | Verdict |
|----------|------|------|---------|
| **Rust** | Zero-cost abstractions, no GC pauses, memory safety at compile time, best-in-class async with Tokio | Steep learning curve, long compile times | ✅ Chosen — critical path, needs sub-ms overhead |
| Go | Simple, fast, good concurrency, GC is low-pause | GC pauses still exist (~1ms), easier to write unsafe code | 🟡 Would work, Rust has edge in pure performance |
| Node.js | Familiar JS, huge ecosystem, event-loop async | Single-threaded, GC pauses, easy to write memory leaks | ❌ Not suitable for crypto-heavy proxy |
| Python | Easiest to write | GIL prevents true parallelism, 10–100× slower | ❌ Way too slow for hot path |

### Why Python for the ML Engine (not Rust)?

The ML ecosystem (PyTorch, ONNX Runtime, HuggingFace, NumPy) is almost entirely Python-first. Implementing a custom transformer training pipeline in Rust would require writing or binding to C++ ML libraries — months of extra work with no benefit, since the ML engine isn't on the hot path (it's a sidecar with a 500ms timeout).

### Why Next.js (not Remix, SvelteKit, Nuxt)?

- **Vercel alignment:** Vercel built Next.js — it deploys perfectly, has zero-config optimization
- **Server Actions:** Directly call server-side code from client components without writing REST endpoints — perfect for auth actions
- **App Router:** Co-locates layouts, loading states, and error boundaries with pages
- **Market dominance:** largest ecosystem of libraries tested with Next.js

### Why Supabase (not Firebase, PlanetScale, Neon)?

| Service | Pros | Cons |
|---------|------|------|
| **Supabase** | PostgreSQL (SQL), row-level security, built-in auth, open-source | Smaller ecosystem than Firebase |
| Firebase | Huge ecosystem, excellent mobile SDKs | NoSQL (Firestore), vendor lock-in, no SQL |
| PlanetScale | Serverless MySQL, branching | MySQL (not PostgreSQL), no built-in auth |
| Neon | Serverless PostgreSQL, branching | No built-in auth, newer/less proven |

PostgreSQL's **Row Level Security (RLS)** is a major advantage — you can write database-level policies like "users can only see rows where `org_id = auth.uid()`", enforced at the database layer regardless of what application code does.

### Why ClickHouse (not PostgreSQL, BigQuery, Snowflake)?

| Service | Pros | Cons |
|---------|------|------|
| **ClickHouse** | Fastest columnar analytics, free self-hosted, MergeTree is perfect for time-series | Requires self-hosting (or ClickHouse Cloud), less familiar SQL |
| PostgreSQL | Already in stack, familiar | Terrible for analytics — row-based, much slower for aggregations |
| BigQuery | Serverless, Google-managed | Expensive at scale, slow for small queries, vendor lock-in |
| Snowflake | Enterprise analytics | Very expensive, overkill for a startup |

### Why Redis (not Memcached, DynamoDB, Postgres)?

Redis has **Lua scripting** — this is the killer feature for the atomic budget check. No other in-memory store supports server-side scripting that executes atomically. DynamoDB has conditional writes but no Lua. Memcached has zero scripting support. This one feature justified the choice.

